  "prompt": "Why is 2000 rupee note introduced and the 1000 rupee note is scraped? Why can't 1000 note also be changed to new ones like the 500?",
  "response": "The introduction of the 2000 rupee note and the scrapping of the 1000 rupee note in India were part of a demonetization move announced by the Prime Minister Narendra Modi on November 8, 2016. There are several reasons behind these decisions:\n\n1. **Curb Black Money and Counterfeiting**:\n   The demonetization aimed to tackle the issues of black money and the circulation of counterfeit currency. It was believed that large denominations like the 1000 rupee note were being used for hoarding illicit wealth, so removing them from circulation would make it more difficult to hide and use large sums of money illicitly.\n\n2. **Introduction of New Features**:\n   The old notes were replaced with new ones that included enhanced security features to help prevent counterfeiting. Introducing a new denomination, like the 2000 rupee note, also served as a means to transition the currency system while providing higher liquidity.\n\n3. **Financial Inclusion and Digital Payments**:\n   The move aimed to promote cashless transactions and financial inclusion by encouraging people to deposit their old notes into banks and switch to digital payment methods. This increased financial transparency and encouraged the use of formal banking channels.\n\n4. **Transition to New Currency**:\n   Replacing old notes with new ones helps to refresh the currency system. When the government decided to scrap the 1000 rupee note, they opted to introduce higher denominations like the 2000 rupee note to reduce the volume of cash needed for transactions, thereby easing the transition and circulation processes.\n\n5. **Addressing Cash Handling and Logistics**:\n   The introduction of the 2000 rupee note facilitated easier cash management and logistics. Higher denominations reduce the bulk of cash that people need to carry for large transactions, thus simplifying the handling of cash for both consumers and businesses.\n\nThe combination of these factors led to the decision to scrap the 1000 rupee note instead of simply replacing it with an updated version, while simultaneously introducing the 2000 rupee note to provide higher liquidity and ease the transition.",
